===Etymology===
Widely assumed to be from {{compound|grape|fruit|lang=en}}, an allusion to the supposed grapelike clusters of fruit on the tree.  Ciardi proposes another theory: the pummelo's botanical name is {{taxlink|Citrus grandis|species}}, meaning "great citrus [fruit]", due to the size of its fruit.  A new pummelo variety might first have been called a "greatfruit", and through the process of [[w:Assimilation (phonology)|assimilation]], the word came to be pronounced "grapefruit".

